trans-unit.source: Serves as the abstract base class for HTML server controls that map to HTML elements that are required to have an opening and a closing tag.
The most common controls with a closing tag are the `<form>`, `<table>`, `<tr>`, `<td>`, `<a>`, and `<span>` elements.

The <xref:System.Web.UI.HtmlControls.HtmlContainerControl.InnerText%2A> and <xref:System.Web.UI.HtmlControls.HtmlContainerControl.InnerHtml%2A> properties allow you to manipulate the content between the opening and closing tags of <xref:System.Web.UI.HtmlControls.HtmlContainerControl>-derived controls.
For a list of initial property values for an instance of <xref:System.Web.UI.HtmlControls.HtmlContainerControl>, see the <xref:System.Web.UI.HtmlControls.HtmlContainerControl.%23ctor%2A> constructor.
A new instance of this class is not created directly.

If you use the <xref:System.Web.UI.HtmlControls.HtmlContainerControl.InnerHtml%2A> property to specify the text between the opening and closing tags of an HTML server control, the text is not HTML encoded.
This makes it possible to embed script within HTML tags in the text.
When using the <xref:System.Web.UI.HtmlControls.HtmlContainerControl.InnerHtml%2A> property, be sure to validate the value to reduce security vulnerabilities.
Otherwise, consider using the <xref:System.Web.UI.HtmlControls.HtmlContainerControl.InnerText%2A> property instead.
Initializes a new instance of the <xref href="System.Web.UI.HtmlControls.HtmlContainerControl"></xref> class using default values.
Use this constructor to create and initialize a new instance of the <xref:System.Web.UI.HtmlControls.HtmlContainerControl> class using default values.
An instance of this class is not created directly.
This constructor is called from the constructor of other HTML control classes to initialize properties defined in this class.
The following table shows initial property values for an instance of <xref:System.Web.UI.HtmlControls.HtmlContainerControl>.
Property
Initial Value
The "span" literal string.
Initializes a new instance of the <xref href="System.Web.UI.HtmlControls.HtmlContainerControl"></xref> class using the specified tag name.
Use this constructor to create and initialize a new instance of the <xref:System.Web.UI.HtmlControls.HtmlContainerControl> class using the specified tag.
An instance of this class is not created directly.
This constructor is called from the constructor of other HTML control classes to initialize properties defined in this class.
The following table shows initial property values for an instance of <xref:System.Web.UI.HtmlControls.HtmlContainerControl>.
Property
Initial Value
The value specified by the `tag` parameter.
A string that specifies the tag name of the control.
Creates a new <xref href="System.Web.UI.ControlCollection"></xref> object to hold the child controls (both literal and server) of the server control.
A <xref href="System.Web.UI.ControlCollection"></xref> that contains the <xref href="System.Web.UI.HtmlControls.HtmlControl"></xref> child server controls.
Gets or sets the content found between the opening and closing tags of the specified HTML server control.
Use the <xref:System.Web.UI.HtmlControls.HtmlContainerControl.InnerHtml%2A> property to programmatically modify the contents between the opening and closing tags of an HTML server control.
The <xref:System.Web.UI.HtmlControls.HtmlContainerControl.InnerHtml%2A> property does not automatically encode special characters to and from HTML entities.
HTML entities allow you to display special characters, such as the `<` character, that a browser would ordinarily interpret as having special meaning.
The `<` character would be interpreted as the start of a tag and is not displayed on the page.
To display the `<` character, you would need to use the entity `<`.
For example, if the property is set to `" Hello "`, the `<` and `>` characters are not converted to `<` and `>`, respectively.
The rendered output would still be: \ Hello \.
The browser will detect the `<b>` tags and display the text, Hello, in a bold font.
Because the text is not HTML encoded, it possible to embed script within HTML tags in the text.
If this property is set dynamically using user input, be sure to validate the value to reduce security vulnerabilities.
For more information, see [Security and User Input](~/docs/standard/security/security-and-user-input.md).
To provide automatic HTML encoding and decoding, use the <xref:System.Web.UI.HtmlControls.HtmlContainerControl.InnerText%2A> property.
If there are no child controls, the <xref:System.Web.UI.HtmlControls.HtmlContainerControl.InnerHtml%2A> property contains the value <xref:System.String.Empty?displayProperty=fullName>.
The HTML content between opening and closing tags of an HTML server control.
There is more than one HTML server control.
\- or -
The HTML server control is not a <xref href="System.Web.UI.LiteralControl"></xref> or a <xref href="System.Web.UI.DataBoundLiteralControl"></xref>.
Gets or sets the text between the opening and closing tags of the specified HTML server control.
Use the <xref:System.Web.UI.HtmlControls.HtmlContainerControl.InnerText%2A> property to programmatically modify the text between the opening and closing tags of an HTML server control.

Unlike the <xref:System.Web.UI.HtmlControls.HtmlContainerControl.InnerHtml%2A> property, the <xref:System.Web.UI.HtmlControls.HtmlContainerControl.InnerText%2A> property automatically encodes special characters to and from HTML entities.
HTML entities allow you to display special characters, such as the `<` character, that a browser would ordinarily interpret as having special meaning.
The `<` character would be interpreted as the start of a tag and is not displayed on the page.
To display the `<` character, you would need to use the entity `<`.
For example, if the property is set to `" Hello "`, the `<` and `>` symbols are converted to `<` and `>`, respectively.
The rendered output would be: < b > Hello < /b >.
The `<` and `>` entities would indicate to the browser that these characters are to be displayed on the page.
The browser will not detect the `<b>` tags and display the text in a bold font.
The text displayed on the page is: \ Hello \.
To prevent automatic HTML encoding and decoding, use the <xref:System.Web.UI.HtmlControls.HtmlContainerControl.InnerHtml%2A> property.
If there are no child controls, the <xref:System.Web.UI.HtmlControls.HtmlContainerControl.InnerHtml%2A> property contains the value <xref:System.String.Empty?displayProperty=fullName>.
The text between the opening and closing tags of an HTML server control.
There is more than one HTML server control.
\- or -
The HTML server control is not a <xref href="System.Web.UI.LiteralControl"></xref> or a <xref href="System.Web.UI.DataBoundLiteralControl"></xref>.

Restores the <xref href="System.Web.UI.HtmlControls.HtmlContainerControl"></xref> control's view state from a previous page request that was saved by the <xref href="System.Web.UI.Control.SaveViewState"></xref> method.
This method is used primarily by the .NET Framework infrastructure and is not intended to be used directly from your code.
However, control developers can override this method to specify how a custom server control restores its view state.
For more information, see [ASP.NET State Management Overview](http://msdn.microsoft.com/library/0218d965-5d30-445b-b6a6-8870e70e63ce).
The <xref:System.Web.UI.HtmlControls.HtmlContainerControl.LoadViewState%2A> method calls the base class's <xref:System.Web.UI.Control.LoadViewState%2A> method.
In addition, the <xref:System.Web.UI.HtmlControls.HtmlContainerControl.LoadViewState%2A> method sets the <xref:System.Web.UI.HtmlControls.HtmlContainerControl.InnerHtml%2A> property.
An <xref href="System.Object"></xref> that represents the control state to be restored.
Renders the <xref href="System.Web.UI.HtmlControls.HtmlContainerControl"></xref> control to the specified <xref href="System.Web.UI.HtmlTextWriter"></xref> object.

The <xref:System.Web.UI.HtmlControls.HtmlContainerControl.Render%2A> method overrides the <xref:System.Web.UI.HtmlControls.HtmlControl.Render%2A?displayProperty=fullName> method to render the opening tag, child controls, and closing tag of the <xref:System.Web.UI.HtmlControls.HtmlContainerControl> control.

The <xref:System.Web.UI.HtmlControls.HtmlContainerControl.Render%2A> method is used primarily by control developers extending the functionality of the <xref:System.Web.UI.HtmlControls.HtmlContainerControl> control.
The <xref href="System.Web.UI.HtmlTextWriter"></xref> that receives the <xref href="System.Web.UI.HtmlControls.HtmlContainerControl"></xref> content.
Renders the <xref href="System.Web.UI.HtmlControls.HtmlContainerControl"></xref> control's attributes to the specified <xref href="System.Web.UI.HtmlTextWriter"></xref> object.
The <xref href="System.Web.UI.HtmlTextWriter"></xref> instance that receives the rendered content.
Renders the closing tag for the <xref href="System.Web.UI.HtmlControls.HtmlContainerControl"></xref> control to the specified <xref href="System.Web.UI.HtmlTextWriter"></xref> object.

The <xref:System.Web.UI.HtmlControls.HtmlContainerControl.RenderEndTag%2A> method is called by the <xref:System.Web.UI.HtmlControls.HtmlContainerControl.Render%2A> method to render the closing tag of the <xref:System.Web.UI.HtmlControls.HtmlContainerControl> control.

The <xref:System.Web.UI.HtmlControls.HtmlContainerControl.RenderEndTag%2A> method is used primarily by control developers extending the functionality of the <xref:System.Web.UI.HtmlControls.HtmlContainerControl> control.
The <xref href="System.Web.UI.HtmlTextWriter"></xref> that receives the rendered content.
